@sijie 
With 4.9, the new producer will not have to worry about the exception, as the conditional update will succeed in this case. If the previous owner's attempt to close wins, the new owner's recovery close will fail, reread the metadata, see that the metadata is no longer in IN_RECOVERY state, so it can assume it is in CLOSED state. Since it is in closed state, it can just take the CLOSED metadata and use that.

https://github.com/apache/bookkeeper/blob/4c8587715104cde6dbd70d1e7de0fc1853122eda/bookkeeper-server/src/main/java/org/apache/bookkeeper/client/ReadOnlyLedgerHandle.java#L313

@sautran The code there should be like : 

```java
 private K getKey(String topic, Message<byte[]> msg) {
        if (!msg.hasKey()) {
            return null;
        }

        if (keyDeserializer instanceof StringDeserializer) {
            return (K) msg.getKey();
        } else {
            // Assume base64 encoding
            byte[] data = Base64.getDecoder().decode(msg.getKey());
            return keyDeserializer.deserialize(topic, data);
        }
    }
```

Did you set the `StringDeserializer` for the key?

@merlimat , yes, I set the key as StringSerializer
props.put("key.serializer", 
                StringSerializer.class.getName());

@merlimat @sijie @jiazhai 
I can't reproduce this issue in master branch, i think this PR #3079 can get around this issue.
The key point of issue #3131 is use totalRedeliveryCount([logic in broker](https://github.com/apache/pulsar/blob/master/pulsar-broker/src/main/java/org/apache/pulsar/broker/service/Consumer.java#L657)) to release permits limit in dispatcher. But after PR #3079 changes will let broker use permitsReceivedWhileConsumerBlocked to release permits limit when consumer is blocked.

